<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<worksheet>
  <title>TF-1 Right Triangle Trigonometry</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      This outcome covers using right triangles to solve problems involving trigonometric 
      ratios. You should be able to use the definitions of the six trigonometric functions to 
      find missing sides and angles in right triangles. You should also be able to apply these 
      skills to solve trigonometric functions of any point in the coordinate plane.
      
    </p>
    <p>For the quiz on this outcome you would be given 30 minutes to complete 2 problems. Here are samples 
      of the types of problems you will encounter:</p>
  </introduction>
  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Simplifying Expressions: Simplify algebraic expressions by combining like terms and applying the 
        distributive property. Answers should be completely simplified.</p></li>
        <li><p>Basics of Graphing: Give a graph with appropriate scales and labels. The line should have the 
          correct intercepts and general behavior.</p></li>
      <li><p>Problem structure: Solution should be organized and easy to follow, with clear, complete steps 
        that follow progressively from one to the next.</p></li>
      <li><p>Mathematical Communication: Solutions should be presented in a clear and logical manner, with 
        appropriate use of mathematical notation and terminology. Equations should have at most one equal 
        sign and expressions on both sides.</p></li>
      <li><p>Solve a right triange: Given two sides of a right triangle, find the missing side and use the 
        trigonometric definitions to find the values of the six trigonometric functions.</p></li>
      <li><p>Find the trigonometric functions of a point: Given a point in the coordinate plane, draw the 
        angle in standard position; draw and label the reference triangle. Find the values of the 
        six trigonometric functions using the definitions of the trigonometric functions and the signs 
        based on the quadrants in the coordinate plane.</p></li>
    </ul>
    </objectives>

  
  <page>
    <exercise workspace="3cm">
      <introduction><p>
           Given the function <m>f(x)=\frac{1}{2}x^2+5x+8</m>.
        </p></introduction>
        <task>
            <statement><p>Write the function in vertex form.</p></statement>
            <hint><p>Use the method of completing the square to rewrite the 
              function in vertex form.</p></hint>
            <answer><p><m>f(x)=\frac{1}{2}(x+5)^2-\frac{9}{2}</m></p></answer>
            <solution><p>Starting with <m>f(x)=\frac{1}{2}x^2+5x+8</m>, we factor 
              out the coefficient of <m>x^2</m> from the first two terms:</p>
            <p><m>f(x)=\frac{1}{2}(x^2+10x)+8</m></p>
            <p>To complete the square, we take half of the coefficient of <m>x</m> 
              and square it: <m>\left(\frac{10}{2}\right)^2 = 5^2 = 25</m>.</p>
            <p>We add this value inside the parentheses and subtract this value 
              multiplied by the coefficient to the outside of the parentheses:</p>
            <p><m>f(x)=\frac{1}{2}(x^2+10x+25)-\frac{1}{2}(25)+8</m></p>
            <p>We can now simplify the perfect square trinomial and the constant term:</p>
            <p><m>f(x)=\frac{1}{2}[(x+5)^2]-\frac{25}{2}+\frac{16}{2}</m></p>
            <p>Simplifying:</p>
            <p><m>f(x)=\frac{1}{2}(x+5)^2-\frac{9}{2}</m></p>
        </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement><p>State the intercepts.</p></statement>
            <hint><p>To find the y-intercept, evaluate the function at <m>x=0</m>. To 
              find the x-intercepts, set the function equal to zero and solve for <m>x</m>.</p></hint>
            <answer><p>y-intercept: <m>(0,8)</m>, x-intercepts: <m>(-2,0)</m> and <m>(-8,0)</m></p></answer>
            <solution><p>To find the y-intercept, we evaluate the function at <m>x=0</m>:</p>
            <p><m>f(0)=\frac{1}{2}(0)^2+5(0)+8=8</m></p>
            <p>Thus, the y-intercept is <m>(0,8)</m>.</p>
            <p>To find the x-intercepts, we set the function equal to zero and solve for 
              <m>x</m>:</p>
            <p><m>0=\frac{1}{2}x^2+5x+8</m></p>
            <p>Multiplying both sides by 2 to clear the fraction:</p>
            <p><m>0=x^2+10x+16</m></p>
            <p>We can now factor the quadratic:</p>
            <p><m>0=(x+5)^2-25+16</m></p>
            <p><m>0=(x+5)^2-9</m></p>
            <p><m>(x+5)^2=9</m></p>
            <p><m>x+5=\pm 3</m></p>
            <p><m>x=-5\pm 3</m></p>
            <p>Thus, the x-intercepts are <m>(-5+3,0)</m> and <m>(-5-3,0)</m>, which 
              can be written as <m>(-2,0)</m> and <m>(-8,0)</m>.</p>
        </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement><p>State the range.</p></statement>
            <hint><p>Look at the leading coefficient and the k-value of the vertex form.</p></hint>
            <answer><p><m>\left[-\frac{9}{2},\infty\right)</m></p></answer>
            <solution><p>Since the coefficient of <m>x^2</m> is positive, the parabola opens 
              upwards. The vertex represents the minimum point of the function, so the 
              range starts at the y-coordinate of the vertex and extends to infinity. This gives
            us the range <m>\left[-\frac{9}{2},\infty\right)</m>.</p>
        </solution>
        </task>
        
    </exercise>
   
  </page>
</worksheet>